You look at something like trade, for example. \'a0We live in an age of global supply chains, and cargo ships that crisscross oceans, and online commerce that can render borders obsolete. \'a0And a lot of folks have legitimate concerns with the way globalization has progressed -- that's one of the changes that's been taking place -- jobs shipped overseas, trade deals that sometimes put workers and businesses at a disadvantage. \'a0But the answer isn\'92t to stop trading with other countries. \'a0In this global economy, that\'92s not even possible. \'a0The answer is to do trade the right way, by negotiating with other countries so that they raise their labor standards and their environmental standards; and we make sure they don\'92t impose unfair tariffs on American goods or steal American intellectual property. \'a0That\'92s how we make sure that international rules are consistent with our values -- including human rights. \'a0And ultimately, that's how we help raise wages here in America. \'a0That\'92s how we help our workers compete on a level playing field. \'a0\
