Look, I'm not suggesting that cold analysis and hard data are ultimately more important in life than passion, or faith, or love, or loyalty. \'a0I am suggesting that those highest expressions of our humanity can only flourish when our economy functions well, and proposed budgets add up, and our environment is protected. \'a0And to accomplish those things, to make collective decisions on behalf of a common good, we have to use our heads. \'a0We have to agree that facts and evidence matter. \'a0And we got to hold our leaders and ourselves accountable to know what the heck they\'92re talking about. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0 \'a0\
All right. \'a0I only have two more points. \'a0I know it's getting cold and you guys have to graduate. \'a0(Laughter.) \'a0Point four: \'a0Have faith in democracy. \'a0Look, I know it\'92s not always pretty. \'a0 Really, I know. \'a0(Laughter.) \'a0I've been living it. \'a0But it\'92s how, bit by bit, generation by generation, we have made progress in this nation. \'a0That's how we banned child labor. \'a0That's how we cleaned up our air and our water. \'a0That's how we passed programs like Social Security and Medicare that lifted millions of seniors out of poverty. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0 \'a0\
None of these changes happened overnight. \'a0They didn\'92t happen because some charismatic leader got everybody suddenly to agree on everything. \'a0It didn\'92t happen because some massive political revolution occurred. \'a0It actually happened over the course of years of advocacy, and organizing, and alliance-building, and deal-making, and the changing of public opinion. \'a0It happened because ordinary Americans who cared participated in the political process. \'a0\'a0\
