Look, if you want to change this country for the better, you better start participating. \'a0I'll give you an example on a lot of people\'92s minds right now -- and that\'92s the growing inequality in our economy. \'a0Over much of the last century, we\'92ve unleashed the strongest economic engine the world has ever seen, but over the past few decades, our economy has become more and more unequal. \'a0The top 10 percent of earners now take in half of all income in the U.S. \'a0In the past, it used to be a top CEO made 20 or 30 times the income of the average worker. \'a0Today, it\'92s 300 times more. \'a0And wages aren\'92t rising fast enough for millions of hardworking families. \'a0\
Now, if we want to reverse those trends, there are a bunch of policies that would make a real difference. \'a0We can raise the minimum wage. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0We can modernize our infrastructure. We can invest in early childhood education. \'a0We can make college more affordable. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0We can close tax loopholes on hedge fund managers and take that money and give tax breaks to help families with child care or retirement. \'a0And if we did these things, then we\'92d help to restore the sense that hard work is rewarded and we could build an economy that truly works for everybody. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0\
Now, the reason some of these things have not happened, even though the majority of people approve of them, is really simple. It's not because I wasn\'92t proposing them. \'a0It wasn\'92t because the facts and the evidence showed they wouldn't work. \'a0It was because a huge chunk of Americans, especially young people, do not vote. \'a0\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 In 2014, voter turnout was the lowest since World War II. \'a0Fewer than one in five young people showed up to vote -- 2014. \'a0And the four who stayed home determined the course of this country just as much as the single one who voted. \'a0Because apathy has consequences. \'a0It determines who our Congress is. \'a0It determines what policies they prioritize. \'a0It even, for example, determines whether a really highly qualified Supreme Court nominee receives the courtesy of a hearing and a vote in the United States Senate. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0 \'a0\
And, yes, big money in politics is a huge problem. \'a0We've got to reduce its influence. \'a0Yes, special interests and lobbyists have disproportionate access to the corridors of power. But, contrary to what we hear sometimes from both the left as well as the right, the system isn\'92t as rigged as you think, and it certainly is not as hopeless as you think. \'a0Politicians care about being elected, and they especially care about being reelected. \'a0And if you vote and you elect a majority that represents your views, you will get what you want. \'a0And if you opt out, or stop paying attention, you won\'92t. \'a0It\'92s that simple. (Applause.) \'a0It's not that complicated.\'a0\
Now, one of the reasons that people don\'92t vote is because they don\'92t see the changes they were looking for right away. \'a0Well, guess what -- none of the great strides in our history happened right away. \'a0It took Thurgood Marshall and the NAACP decades to win Brown v. Board of Education; and then another decade after that to secure the Civil Rights Act and the Voting Rights Act. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0And it took more time after that for it to start working. \'a0It took a proud daughter of New Jersey, Alice Paul, years of organizing marches and hunger strikes and protests, and drafting hundreds of pieces of legislation, and writing letters and giving speeches, and working with congressional leaders before she and other suffragettes finally helped win women the right to vote. \'a0(Applause.) \'a0\
